# no-no-g0.utb attaches virtual dots to the braille output in order to
# make it possible to distinguish between identical dot patterns that
# originate from different input. For instance, the braille pattern
# for digit "1" has a virtual dot to distinguish it from the letter
# "a".

# no-print.dis maps dot patterns back to their origin as much as
# possible. Special indicator dot patterns are mapped to Unicode
# braille.

# the meaning of the virtual dots is as follows:
#
# - 9: numeric
# - f: uppercase
# - d: greek
# - e: cyrillic
# - a, b and c are used to create at most 7 alternatives for each dot pattern

